(RewardLoopWorker pid=462204, ip=10.124.45.23) <answer>The script used in autographs, particularly the cursive form, evolved over time and is not attributed to a single inventor. However, the Latin script, which forms the basis of many autograph styles, was developed by the Etruscans and later refined by the Romans. The practice of signing one's name as an autograph became more common in the Middle Ages and Renaissance, but no specific individual is credited with inventing the script itself.</answer>
